05216nam a22010215i 9780520958043DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20142014cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2020757170  a97805209580437 a10.1525/97805209580432doi  a(DE-B1597)519503  a(OCoLC)867818478  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aGV840.S8 4aGV840.S8bL33 2016 7aHIS0370002bisacsh04a797.322231 aLaderman, Scott, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEmpire in Waves :bA Political History of Surfing /cScott Laderman. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSport in World History ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: A Political History of Surfing -- t1. How Surfing Became American: The Imperial Roots of Modern Surf Culture -- t2. A World Made Safe for Discovery: Travel, Cultural Diplomacy, and the Politics of Surf Exploration -- t3. Paradise Found: The Discovery of Indonesia and the Surfing Imagination -- t4. When Surfing Discovered It Was Political: Confronting South African Apartheid -- t5. Industrial Surfing: The Commodification of Experience -- tEpilogue: A New Millennium -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSurfing today evokes many things: thundering waves, warm beaches, bikinis and lifeguards, and carefree pleasure. But is the story of surfing really as simple as popular culture suggests? In this first international political history of the sport, Scott Laderman shows that while wave riding is indeed capable of stimulating tremendous pleasure, its globalization went hand in hand with the blood and repression of the long twentieth century.   Emerging as an imperial instrument in post-annexation Hawaii, spawning a form of tourism that conquered the littoral Third World, tracing the struggle against South African apartheid, and employed as a diplomatic weapon in America's Cold War arsenal, the saga of modern surfing is only partially captured by Gidget, the Beach Boys, and the film Blue Crush. From nineteenth-century American empire-building in the Pacific to the low-wage labor of the surf industry today, Laderman argues that surfing in fact closely mirrored American foreign relations. Yet despite its less-than-golden past, the sport continues to captivate people worldwide. Whether in El Salvador or Indonesia or points between, the modern history of this cherished pastime is hardly an uncomplicated story of beachside bliss. Sometimes messy, occasionally contentious, but never dull, surfing offers us a whole new way of viewing our globalized world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSurfingxHistory. 0aSurfingxPolitical aspects. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh  aamerican foreign relations.  aamerican imperialism.  aapartheid.  aathletes.  abeaches.  ablue crush.  acold war.  acommodification.  adiplomacy.  aempire.  agidget.  aglobalization.  ahawaii.  ahistory of surfing.  ahistory.  aimperialism.  aindividual sports.  aindonesia.  aindustrial surfing.  ainternational politics.  along 20th century.  alow wage labor.  amodern surf culture.  aocean.  apolitical history of surfing.  apolitics.  arepression.  asouth africa.  asports.  asurfing today.  asurfing.  athe beach boys.  atourism.  aunited states of america.  awave riding.  awaves.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052027910040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095804340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520958043423Coveruhttps://www.degru